{"cursor":"4839","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Cleo Paskal' is an Associate Fellow at Chatham House, (aka Royal Institute of\nInternational Affairs), Adjunct Faculty in the Department of Geopolitics,\nManipal University, India and Adjunct Professor of Global Change, School of\nCommunication and Management Studies, Kochi, India. Her book, Global Warring:\nHow Environmental, Economic and Political Crises Will Redraw the World Map\n(Palgrave Macmillan, 2010) won a US$5000 Awards of Merit in the 2010 Grantham\nPrize for Excellence in Reporting on the Environment awards as well as the 2010\nMavis Gallant Prize for Non-Fiction. She also co-authored the bestseller\nSpielball Erde: MachtkÃ¤mpfe im Klimawandel (Random House, 2012), with German tv\nnews anchor Claus Kleber.\n\nPaskal is a geopolitical expert who specializes in the confluence of the \"three\ngeos\" (the geopolitical, geoeconomic, and geophysical). This includes the\ngeopolitical, security, and economic implications of evironmental change\n(including climate change), as well as Arctic and Pacific security.\n\nQuote of Mohamed Nasheed, President of the Maldives, from Global Warring: \"We\ncan do nothing to stop climate change on our own and so we have to buy land\nelsewhere. It's an insurance policy for the worst possible outcome. After all,\nthe Israelis (began by buying) land in Palestine.\" Paskal, Cleo, Global\nWarring: How Environmental, Economic and Political Crises Will Redraw the World\nMap, Key Porter Books, Canada, 2010 & Palgrave Macmillan, US, UK (ISBN 978-\n0230621817), p. 189 [http://www.globalwarring.com]\n\nOther published research includes a Chatham House Briefing Paper on how climate\nchange might affect borders [http://www.chathamhouse.org.uk/research/eedp/papers/view/-\n/id/499/] (Paskal was the first to publish on the critical issue of how sea\nlevel rise can affect exclusive economic zone claims), a new method for\nassessing a state or region's vulnerability to environmental change [http://www.chinadialogue.net/homepage/show/single/en/1634-Three-R-s-for-\nsurviving-environmental-change], the concept of [http://www.chinadialogue.net/article/show/single/en/2058-Nationalistic-\ncapitalism-and-the-food-crisis Nationalistic Capitalism], a policy paper for the\nCommission on National Security in the 21st Century on the effects of\nenvironmental change on UK national security\n[http://www.ippr.org/publicationsandreports/publication.asp?id=657], a Chatham\nHouse Briefing Paper on vulnerability of energy infrastructure to environmental\nchange [http://www.chathamhouse.org.uk/publications/papers/view/-/id/737/], and\na Journal of International Security Affairs paper on how environmental change\ncan undermine major components of global and national\n[http://www.securityaffairs.org/issues/2010/18/paskal.php legal systems].\n\nShe has also looked at a range of other strategic topics, including balance of\npower issues in the [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/cleo-paskal/why-the-west-is-losing-\nth_b_786668.html Pacific], and [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/cleo-paskal/indian-\ncorruption_b_931981.html corruption] in India and China. She has briefed\nofficials from over two dozen governments, and was a consultant for the U.S.\nDepartment of Energy's \"Global Energy and Environment Strategic Ecosystem\".\n\nCleo Paskal is also an award-winning journalist who has contributed to, among\nothers, [[The Economist]], [[The Independent]], and the [[The Sunday Times\n(UK)|Sunday Times]]. She has hosted BBC radio shows and wrote an Emmy-winning TV\nseries. She has had columns with the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation,\n[[National Post]] and the [[Toronto Star]]. Having attended McGill University,\nshe co-founded that school's satire magazine, The Red Herring. She also wrote\nthe Primetime Emmy Award winning TV series [[Cirque du Soleil]]: Fire Within.\nShe is a Huffington Post [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/cleo-paskal blogger].\n","linknr":292,"url":"Cleo_Paskal","recorded":1364046081,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Cleo_Paskal&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Cleo_Paskal&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/Chatham_House","/wiki/Royal_Institute_of_International_Affairs","/wiki/Geopolitics","/wiki/Manipal_University","/wiki/India","/wiki/School_of_Communication_and_Management_Studies","/wiki/Kochi,_India","/wiki/Palgrave_Macmillan","/wiki/Grantham_Prize_for_Excellence_in_Reporting_on_the_Environment","/wiki/Mavis_Gallant_Prize_for_Non-Fiction","/wiki/Random_House","/wiki/Claus_Kleber","/wiki/Climate_change","/wiki/Mohamed_Nasheed","/wiki/Maldives","/wiki/Demographics_of_Israel","/wiki/Ottoman_Syria","#cite_note-1","http://www.chathamhouse.org.uk/research/eedp/papers/view/-/id/499/","/wiki/Sea_level_rise","/wiki/Exclusive_economic_zone","http://www.chinadialogue.net/homepage/show/single/en/1634-Three-R-s-for-surviving-environmental-change","http://www.chinadialogue.net/article/show/single/en/2058-Nationalistic-capitalism-and-the-food-crisis","http://www.ippr.org/publicationsandreports/publication.asp?id=657","/wiki/Chatham_House","http://www.chathamhouse.org.uk/publications/papers/view/-/id/737/","http://www.securityaffairs.org/issues/